ce:section.ce:para:
According to an earlier study, S-CDs can enter dead bacterial cells and further stain them [64]. In the present study, the S-CDs were used as cellular fluorescent dyes to identify dead C. albicans. Notably, S-CDs can penetrate the damaged cell membranes of C. albicans but cannot enter fungal cells with intact cell membranes. To confirm this, S-CDs were incubated with stained live or dead C. albicans treated with Cu/I-CDs under the light condition (LED 16 W) before photographs of the cells were taken. No fluorescent images of the fungi in the control group were obtained (
                        Fig. 7
                        ). In the groups treated only with Cu/I-CDs or H2O2, only a few dead fungal cells were observed, indicating that these compounds exhibit negligible ability to inhibit fungal growth. In contrast, a large number of dead fungi in the Cu/I-CDs + H2O2 group were invaded by S-CDs, and the cell morphology could be observed clearly, indicating that the Cu/I-CDs + H2O2 regimen had a strong antifungal effect, which might have been achieved by a mechanism involving the destruction of fungal cell membranes by generated ROS.
